Sunday Nwakanma,  Umuahia Abia State Governor, Okezie Ikpeazu, Monday presented a budget of N131.8bn to the Abia State Assembly. Christened ‘Budget of Local Contents and Sustainable Development,’ the budget showed an increase of 22.12 per cent from the 2020 revised budget of N102.6bn. The governor explained that the percentage of distribution of aggregate expenditures to the 2021 total Budget Outlay is 47.51 per cent for recurrent and 52.49 per cent for capital. The 2021 budget he said, was aimed at completion of on-going projects and programmes, adding “New projects will mainly be in the form of COVID-19 responsive projects that aim to cushion the shocks of the pandemic and assist the State economy recover quickly”. The State, Ikpeazu said, adopted 2021 – 2023 Medium Term Expenditure Framework and Fiscal Strategy Paper of the Federal Government which set out the parameters for the 2021 Budget, including benchmark oil price of 40 US Dollars per barrel. The governor said, “It is the wish of the present Administration to prepare an equitable, realistic and implementable budget in the context of multi-year (2021-2023) Medium Term Expenditure Framework that will be in line with the current economic realities”. The Speaker, Chinedum Orji, assured the governor of the cooperation of the House. Copyright PUNCH.
